Groups of algorithms

  • grouping of algorithms by their learning style
  • grouping of algorithms by their similarity in form or function

Algorithms grouped by learning style

  • Supervised Learning:
    • input data is called training data and has a known label/target variable
    • example problems are classification and regression
    • example algorithms include: Logistic Regression and the Back Propagation Neural Network
  • Unsupervised Learning:
    • input data is not labeled and does not have a known result
    • a model is prepared by deducing structures present in the input data
    • example problems are clustering, dimensionality reduction and association rule learning
    • example algorithms include: the Apriori algorithm and K-Means
  • Semi-Supervised Learning:
    • input data is a mixture of labeled and unlabelled examples
    • example problems are classification and regression
    • example algorithms are extensions to other flexible methods that make assumptions about how to model the unlabeled data

Algorithms grouped by similarity

  • a useful grouping method, but it is not perfect
  • still algorithms that could just as easily fit into multiple categories like Learning Vector Quantization
  • groups:
    • regression algorithms
    • instance-based algorithms
    • regularization algorithms
    • decision tree algorithms
    • Bayesian algorithms
    • clustering algorithms
    • association rule learning algorithms
    • artificial neural network algorithms
    • deep learning algorithms
    • dimensionality reduction algorithms
    • ensemble algorithms
    • other machine learning algorithms

Regression algorithms

  • modeling the relationship between variables that is iteratively refined using a measure of error in the predictions made by the model
  • Ordinary Least Squares Regression (OLSR)
  • Linear Regression
  • Logistic Regression
  • Stepwise Regression
  • Multivariate Adaptive Regression Splines (MARS)
  • Locally Estimated Scatterplot Smoothing (LOESS)

Instance-based algorithms

  • typically build up a database of example data and compare new data to the database using a similarity measure in order to find the best match and make a prediction
  • k-Nearest Neighbor (kNN)
  • Learning Vector Quantization (LVQ)
  • Self-Organizing Map (SOM)
  • Locally Weighted Learning (LWL)
  • Support Vector Machines (SVM)

Regularization algorithms

  • an extension made to another method (typically regression methods) that penalizes models based on their complexity, favoring simpler models that are also better at generalizing
  • Ridge Regression
  • Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator (LASSO)
  • Elastic Net
  • Least-Angle Regression (LARS)

Decision trees algorithms

  • decisions fork in tree structures until a prediction decision is made for a given record
  • often fast and accurate and a big favorite in machine learning
  • Classification and Regression Tree (CART)
  • Iterative Dichotomiser 3 (ID3)
  • C4.5 and C5.0 (different versions of a powerful approach)
  • Chi-squared Automatic Interaction Detection (CHAID)
  • Decision Stump
  • M5
  • Conditional Decision Trees

Bayesian algorithms

  • explicitly apply Bayes’ Theorem for problems such as classification and regression
  • Naive Bayes
  • Gaussian Naive Bayes
  • Multinomial Naive Bayes
  • Averaged One-Dependence Estimators (AODE)
  • Bayesian Belief Network (BBN)
  • Bayesian Network (BN)

Clustering algorithms

  • typically organized by the modeling approaches such as centroid-based and hierarchical
  • k-Means
  • k-Medians
  • Expectation Maximisation (EM)
  • Hierarchical Clustering

Association rule learning algorithms

  • extract rules that best explain observed relationships between variables in data
  • Apriori algorithm
  • Frequent pattern growth algorithm (FP growth)
  • Eclat algorithm

Artificial neural network algorithms

  • models that are inspired by the structure and/or function of biological neural networks
  • Perceptron
  • Multilayer Perceptrons (MLP)
  • Back-Propagation
  • Stochastic Gradient Descent
  • Hopfield Network
  • Radial Basis Function Network (RBFN)

Deep learning algorithms

  • a modern update to Artificial Neural Networks that exploit abundant cheap computation
  • Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)
  • Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs)
  • Long Short-Term Memory Networks (LSTMs)
  • Stacked Auto-Encoders
  • Deep Boltzmann Machine (DBM)
  • Deep Belief Networks (DBN)

Dimensionality reduction algorithms

  • dmensionality reduction seek and exploit the inherent structure in the data, but in this case in an unsupervised manner or order to summarize or describe data using less information
  • Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
  • Principal Component Regression (PCR)
  • Partial Least Squares Regression (PLSR)
  • Sammon Mapping
  • Multidimensional Scaling (MDS)
  • Projection Pursuit
  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)
  • Mixture Discriminant Analysis (MDA)
  • Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)
  • Flexible Discriminant Analysis (FDA)

Ensemble algorithms

  • models composed of multiple weaker models that are independently trained and whose predictions are combined in some way to make the overall prediction
  • Boosting
  • Bootstrapped Aggregation (Bagging)
  • AdaBoost
  • Weighted Average (Blending)
  • Stacked Generalization (Stacking)
  • Gradient Boosting Machines (GBM)
  • Gradient Boosted Regression Trees (GBRT)
  • Random Forest

Other machine learning algorithms

Linear regression - 1

  • it is both a statistical algorithm and a machine learning algorithm
  • an attractive model because the representation is so simple

  • preprocess data:
    • remove noise (removing outliers, especially in the output variable)
    • remove collinearity (danger of overfitting)
    • linear regression will make more reliable predictions if your input and output variables have a Gaussian distribution
    • rescale input

Linear regression - 2

  • METRICS:
    • Mean Absolute Error (MAE): measures the average of the absolute difference between each ground truth and the predictions
    • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): measures the square root of the average of the squared difference between the predictions and the ground truth; is more sensitive to outliers
    • MAE/RMSE must be compared with the dependent variable
    • R-Squared: o understand how well the independent variables “explain” the variance in your model, the R-Squared formula can be powerful
    • Adjusted R-squared: adds a penalty to the model for every additional variable

Linear regression - 3

  • PROS:
    • is simple to implement and easier to interpret the output coefficient
  • CONS:
    • outliers can have huge effects on the regression
    • most of the problems aren’t linear
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: lm
    • Python: sklearn

Logistic regression - 1

  • another technique borrowed by machine learning from the field of statistics
  • simple logistic regression (binary)
  • Sigmoid Function
  • modeling the probability that an input (X) belongs to the default class (Y=1)
  • probability prediction must be transformed into a binary values (0 or 1)

Logistic regression - 2

  • multiple logistic regression
  • basically we re-run binary classification multiple times, once for each class
  • Softmax activation
  • METRICS:
    • likelihood ratio test
    • Pseudo R^2: McFadden’s R2 - the measure ranges from 0 to just under 1, with values closer to zero indicating that the model has no predictive power
    • variable importance
    • ROC curve: ranges from 0.50 to 1.00, and values above 0.80 indicate that the model does a good job

Logistic regression - 3

  • PROS:
    • one of the simplest machine learning algorithms
    • inference about the importance of each feature (trained weights)
    • fast
  • CONS:
    • quickly leads to overfitting
    • sensitive to outliers
    • most of the problems aren’t linear
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: glm
    • Python: sklearn

Decision trees - 1

  • non-parametric supervised learning method
  • top - bottom approach; selecting the best attribute (the best attribute is the one with the highest information gain)

Decision trees - 2

  • METRICS:
    • confusion matrix:
    • accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score:
    • cost of FN > cost of FP –> recall; cost of FP > cost of FN –> precision

Decision trees - 3

  • PROS:
    • simple to understand and to interpret. Trees can be visualized
    • requires little data preparation
    • able to handle both numerical and categorical data
  • CONS:
    • easily overfitting (solution pre-pruning and post-pruning)
    • unstable, meaning that a small change in the data can lead to a large change in the structure of the optimal decision tree
    • decision tree algorithm is inadequate for applying regression and predicting continuous values
    • often involves higher time to train the model
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: rpart
    • Python: sklearn

Random forest - 1

  • consists of a large number of individual decision trees that operate as an ensemble
  • predictions (and therefore the errors) made by the individual trees need to have low correlations with each other
  • bagging: allowing each individual tree to randomly sample from the dataset with replacement, resulting in different trees
  • splitting a node: each tree in a random forest can pick only from a random subset of features

Random forest - 2

  • METRICS: the same as for DT
  • PROS:
    • great with High dimensionality
    • quick prediction/training speed
    • robust to outliers and non-linear data
    • hHandles unbalanced data
  • CONS:
    • model interpretability: Random forest models are not all that interpretable; they are like black boxes
    • for very large data sets, the size of the trees can take up a lot of memory
    • tends to overfit, so you should tune the hyperparameters
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: randomForest
    • Python: sklearn

Adabost - 1

  • an ensemble algorithm
  • AdaBoost is best used to boost the performance of decision trees on binary classification problems

## Adabost - 2 {.smaller}

  • METRICS: the same as for DT
  • PROS:
    • very good use of weak classifiers for cascading
    • different classification algorithms can be used as weak classifiers
    • AdaBoost has a high degree of precision
  • CONS:
    • data imbalance leads to a decrease in classification accuracy
    • training is time consuming
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: adaboost
    • Python: sklearn

SVM - 1

  • machine learning algorithms which are used both for classification and regression; but generally, they are used in classification problems
  • the decision boundary that maximizes the distance (maximum margin classifier) from the nearest data points of all the classes

  • the decision boundary doesn’t have to be a line; it’s also referred to as a hyperplane because you can find the decision boundary with any number of features, not just two
  • SVM algorithms aren’t scale invariant

SVM - 2

  • METRICS: the same as for DT
  • PROS:
    • Effective on datasets with multiple features, like financial or medical data
    • memory efficient
  • CONS:
    • SVMs don’t directly provide probability estimates
    • works best on small sample sets because of its high training time
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: svm
    • Python: sklearn

FP-growth - 1

  • market basket analysis
  • represents the database in the form of a tree called a frequent pattern tree or FP tree
  • the database is fragmented using one frequent item
  • the itemsets of these fragmented patterns are analyzed
  • PROS:
    • algorithm needs to scan the database only twice when compared to Apriori
    • efficient and scalable for mining both long and short frequent patterns
  • CONS:
    • FP Tree is more cumbersome and difficult to build than Apriori
    • It may be “expensive”

FP-growth - 2

  • METRICS:
    • Support: indication of how frequently the itemset appears in the dataset
    • Confidence: indication of how often the rule has been found to be true
    • Lift: a useful measure to determine the strength of the association between the items in a rule
    • Conviction: the frequency that the rule makes an incorrect prediction if X and Y were independent divided by the observed frequency of incorrect predictions
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: rCBA
    • Python: pyfpgrowth

Neural network: feed-forward - 1

  • biologically inspired classification algorithm
  • every unit in a layer is connected with all the units in the previous layer
  • each connection may have a different strength or weight
  • there is no feedback between layers
  • besides the input pattern, the neural net also needs to know to what category the pattern belongs
  • the units in the output layer all belong to a different category

Neural network: feed-forward - 2

  • the unit with the correct category would have had the largest output value; the output values of the other output units would have been very small
  • on the basis of this comparison all the connection weights are modified a little bit
  • greater modification, faster learning, but usually overshooting
  • the output values are compared with the correct answer to compute the value of some predefined error-function
  • METRICS: the same as for DT (classification)
  • PROS:
    • fast, simple and easy to program
    • it does not require prior knowledge about the network
    • it is a standard method that generally works well

Neural network: feed-forward - 3

  • CONS:
    • can be quite sensitive to noisy data
  • IMPLEMENTATION:
    • R: neuralnet
    • Python: pytorch
